First Man On the Moon
There was a special air of excitement as Apollo 11
lifted off from Cape Canaveral on July 16 with astro-
nauts Neil Armstrong, Buzz Aldrin, and Michael Col-
lins aboard. This was to be the fulfillment of man's
dream since the beginning of time. If all went well,
Armstrong and Aldrin would walk on the moon.
On the afternoon of July 20, the lunar module (LM)
Eagle separated from the mother ship Columbia and
made its historic landing on the moon. After six hours
of preparation, the hatch of the LM finally opened. A
ladder was lowered and Neil Armstrong climbed
down. At precisely 10:56 p.m., eastern time, he set
his boot on the surface of the moon for the first time.
The full-color cachet captures the remarkable mo-
ment when "man on the moon' became a reality. It
shows Neil Armstrong on the last rung of the ladder,
about to step onto the lunar surface. "That's one
small step for a man, one giant leap for mankind,"
he proclaimed.
Mint Stamp: The mint stamp on this Cover was issued
by the United States in 1969. It pictures Armstrong on
the moon with his life support system on his back.
In the background, nearly 250,000 miles away, is
Earth.
Postmark: This Cover was postmarked in Cape Ca-
naveral, Florida, U.S.A. on July 20, 1984, the exact
anniversary of the date on which man first set foot on
the moon.

properties.sfomuseum:description: Airmail flight cover, part of International Tributes to the History of Flight series by the Postal Commemorative Society; white envelope with full color illustration cachet and inset stamp commemorating first man on the moon on July 20, 1969, at Cape Canaveral, Florida, U.S.A., by Neil Armstrong with Apollo 11 “Columbia” spacecraft and “Eagle” lunar module; cancellation stamp dated July 20, 1984 in Cape Canaveral; includes information on reverse.
